I don't think that the class name or the documentation help in understanding when all this is needed, i.e. what is consistency in this case? Is the regular Cache inconsistent?
Similarly with the checkpoint caller. I need to read the code to have any clue of what a checkpoint.put does.
My feeling is that you're trying too hard to hide the lock and the counter.
What do you say of something like:
public class CacheInvalidationHelper<K, V> {

    private final Cache<K, V> cache;
    private final AtomicLong currentInvalidationCounter = new AtomicLong();
    private final ReadWriteLock lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();
    private final ReleasableLock putLock = new ReleasableLock(lock.readLock());
    private final ReleasableLock invalidateLock = new ReleasableLock(lock.writeLock());

    public CacheInvalidationHelper(Cache<K, V> cache) {
        this.cache = cache;
    }

    public Long getCurrentInvalidationCount() {
        return this.currentInvalidationCounter.get();
    }

    public void putIfNoInvalidationSince(K key, V value, Long previousInvalidationCounter) {
        try (ReleasableLock ignored = putLock.acquire()) {
            if (previousInvalidationCounter == currentInvalidationCounter.get()) {
                cache.put(key, value);
            }
        }
    }

    public void invalidate(K key) {
        try (ReleasableLock ignored = invalidateLock.acquire()) {
            currentInvalidationCounter.incrementAndGet();
        }
        cache.invalidate(key);
    }

    public void invalidateAll() {
        try (ReleasableLock ignored = invalidateLock.acquire()) {
            currentInvalidationCounter.incrementAndGet();
        }
        cache.invalidateAll();
    }
}

